Emergency planning and response.
The brewery additionally complies with the requirements of the OSHA PSM standard (40 CFR
1910.119), the EPA RMP rules (40 CFR 68), and applicable Recognized and Generally Accepted
Refrigeration System Practices for Equipment, Design, and Installation of Ammonia Mechanical
Refrigerating Systems.

WORST CASE SCENARIO
As required by the EPA's Risk Management regulations, we have identified an extremely unlikely
"worst-case" scenario in which the Brewhouse Glycol Cooler located outside the Brewhouse (Building 4) fails and releases 100% of its capacity of 4,208 pounds of anhydrous ammonia(5.42 lbs/gal @ 32 psig, 18.6 deg F). Under worst-case weather conditions ,ammonia could travel 1.20 miles before dispersing enough to no longer pose a threat to the public.
This scenario is unlikely to occur at the Fairfield brewery for a number of reasons:
Brewery piping and vessels that contain ammonia meet or exceed industry manufacturing and quality control standards;
Ammonia is not corrosive in the form in which it is used at the brewery;
Pressure relief safety valves limit operating pressures so the chance of a large-scale release is
minimal;
Operating level of the vessel is well below full capacity with routine monitoring and high level safety interlocks; 
Manual safety valves allow the immediate shut-off of the ammonia system;
Equipment is inspected and kept in proper working order and replaced when necessary;
The brewery has an emergency response plan and equipment in place (see emergency response section).

